(a) A summary of takeaways

My first takeaway is the 15 technical indicators in the Appendix, where the authors summarized formulas to calculate these indicators and concrete interpretation of how to use these indicators in technical analysis. My second takeaway is the novel algorithmic trading model that this article uses to develop transaction strategies. It is innovative to convert 1-D financial time series into a 2-D image-like data to utilizing CNN for the trading system. Last but not least, Im impressed by the comparison of annualized returns with the BaH strategy and the other 4 strategies. It is worth noting that the algorithm beat BaH consistently and noticeably.

Stock returns: Take Netflix as an example, I visualized the distribution of returns by day, week, and month. We can see higher standard deviation and lower kurtosis as return periods become longer. This is in line with intuitive because stock returns are more volatile from month to month than from day to day.

Netflix Trading Strategies

# Netflix
macd <- MACD(NFLX$NFLX.Adjusted, nFast = 12, nSlow = 26, nSig = 9, maType = "SMA", percent = FALSE)
rsi <- RSI(NFLX$NFLX.Adjusted, n = 14, maType = "SMA")

# Strategy 1: if macd>signal, enter and stay in the market. If macd<signal, exit the market.
strategy1 <- ifelse ((macd$signal < macd$macd) , 1, 0)
strategy1[is.na(strategy1)] <-0

# Strategy 2: if oversold, enter and stay in the market.
strategy2 <- ifelse ((macd$signal > macd$macd) & (rsi$rsi < 30), 1, 0)
strategy2[is.na(strategy2)] <-0

# Buy-and-hold: keep it all time. So "1", not "0"
bh_strategy <- rep(1,dim(macd)[1])

Backtesting

# Netflix: Buy-and-hold strategy
BH_backtest <- function(df,from_date,to_date,strategy_name){
    rtn.daily <- dailyReturn(df) # returns by day 
    trade_return <- rtn.daily[index(rtn.daily)<=to_date & index(rtn.daily)>=from_date]
    cumm_return <- Return.cumulative(trade_return)
    annual_return <- Return.annualized(trade_return) 
    summary(as.ts(trade_return))
    SharpeRatio <- SharpeRatio(as.ts(trade_return), Rf = 0, p = 0.95, FUN = "StdDev")
    SharpeRatioAnnualized <- SharpeRatio.annualized(trade_return, Rf = 0)
    out <- as.data.frame(c(cumm_return,annual_return,SharpeRatio,SharpeRatioAnnualized))
    out <- round(out,2)
    colnames(out) <- strategy_name
    row.names(out) <- c('Cumulative Return','Annualized Return','Sharpe Ratio','Annualized Sharpe Ratio')
     
  return( out )
    }

buy_and_hold_performance <- BH_backtest(df_N, from_date = '2009-01-01', to_date = '2019-12-31',"Buy & Hold Strategy")
buy_and_hold_performance

backtest <- function(df,from_date,to_date,strategy,strategy_name){
    rtn.daily <- dailyReturn(df) # returns by day 
    trade_return <- rtn.daily[index(rtn.daily)<=to_date & index(rtn.daily)>=from_date]*stats::lag(strategy, na.pad = FALSE)
    cumm_return <- Return.cumulative(trade_return)
    annual_return <- Return.annualized(trade_return) 
    summary(as.ts(trade_return))
    SharpeRatio <- SharpeRatio(as.ts(trade_return), Rf = 0, p = 0.95, FUN = "StdDev")
    SharpeRatioAnnualized <- SharpeRatio.annualized(trade_return, Rf = 0)
    out <- as.data.frame(c(cumm_return,annual_return,SharpeRatio,SharpeRatioAnnualized))
    out <- round(out,2)
    colnames(out) <- strategy_name
    row.names(out) <- c('Cumulative Return','Annualized Return','Sharpe Ratio','Annualized Sharpe Ratio')
    
  return( out )
    }
# Netflix: Strategy 1
strategy1_performance <- backtest(NFLX, from_date = '2009-01-01', to_date = '2019-12-31', strategy1,"Strategy1")

# Macy's
macd <- MACD(M$M.Adjusted, nFast = 12, nSlow = 26, nSig = 9, maType = "SMA", percent = FALSE)

strategy1 <- ifelse ((macd$signal < macd$macd) , 1, 0)
strategy1[is.na(strategy1)] <-0

# Strategy 2: if overbought, enter and stay in the market.
strategy2 <- ifelse ((macd$signal < macd$macd) & (rsi$rsi > 70), 1, 0)
strategy2[is.na(strategy2)] <-0

# Buy-and-hold: keep it all time. So "1", not "0"

From the result of backtesting, we can conclude that for all 3 stocks, buy and hold is the best strategy. However, if we shorten the backtesting time to 6 months, take 3M for example, we can see that Strategy 1 (IF macd>signal, enter and stay in the market. If macd<signal, exit the market) beat BaH. But, since we assume no transaction fees here, the real return will be lower.

First half of 2020

Between Feb and March, inevitably all 3 stock plummeted in the 2020 stock market crash. But Netflix restored quickly and the stock price increased in the following months. The Stay-at-Home Orders prompted the increase of Netflix because streaming is one of the few entertainment options. Macys stock drop represents the struggle of most department stores in the pandemic. But there are already early signs of crisis in department stores with the rise of e-commerce.
